This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it proposes a time-aware ranking model that leverages on multiple sources of crowd signals to predict the temporal relevance of documents for a query. Additionally, the paper also makes use of learning to rank techniques, which is a common approach in IR research. 

The paper could also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category as it deals with the behavior of crowds on microblogging services like Twitter. 

The paper may also be relevant to the Social and Economic Networks (cs.SOC) sub-category as it studies the dynamics of user behavior on the web in response to real-world events. 

The paper could also be relevant to the Computation and Language (cs.CL) sub-category as it deals with the analysis of textual data from multiple sources. 

Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category as it proposes a novel approach for ranking search results that could be applied in software systems.
